            <ArticleTitle>Probing Quantum Capacitance in a 3D Topological Insulator.</ArticleTitle>
            <Pagination>
                <MedlinePgn>166802</MedlinePgn>
            </Pagination>
            <ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1103/PhysRevLett.116.166802</ELocationID>
            <Abstract>
                <AbstractText>We measure the quantum capacitance and probe thus directly the electronic density of states of the high mobility, Dirac type two-dimensional electron system, which forms on the surface of strained HgTe. Here we show that observed magnetocapacitance oscillations probe-in contrast to magnetotransport-primarily the top surface. Capacitance measurements constitute thus a powerful tool to probe only one topological surface and to reconstruct its Landau level spectrum for different positions of the Fermi energy. </AbstractText>
            </Abstract>
